  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering Control Act)\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Monetary Transactions in Criminally Derived Property)\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. State Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n- These often mirror federal provisions but can have additional specific requirements\n\n3. Key International Agreements:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n4. Regulatory Frameworks:\n- FinCEN (Financial Crimes Enforcement Network) regulations\n- IRS reporting requirements\n- Banking regulations\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Impose reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\nThe primary goal is to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
